Yes, there are a few tricks to bypass CORS issues in client-side JavaScript but they should be used with caution as they could override important security measures. To resolve it without involving CORS, you might consider using a proxy server which can make the request on your behalf and then serve the result back to you.

Here's a simple example using express and http-proxy-middleware:

```js
const express = require('express');
const { createProxyMiddleware } = require('http-proxy-middleware');

const app = express();

app.use('/api', createProxyMiddleware({ 
    target: 'http://192.168.68.112:3000', 
    changeOrigin: true 
}));

app.listen(3000, () => console.log('Proxy server running on http://localhost:3000'));
```

This script creates an Express server on port 3000 which proxies any requests to `/api/*` to `http://192.168.68.112:3000/*`.

You can then modify your original AJAX call:

```js
xhr.open('GET', 'http://localhost:3000/api/sensor_data', true);
```

Do note queries via proxies may not be suitable for sensitive data or performance-sensitive applications. It's always better to properly configure your server for CORS if you are in control of the server.

Also note bypassing CORS is only recommended for development purpose and should not be done on a production application as it could lead to security vulnerabilities. 

